<br>
1) One familiar during lifetime.  In the books I've read, a wizard only got one and it was a friend and companion, not some drone like a magician's pet.<br>
<br>
2) Quest for the familiar -- not a spell.  This has to do again with the nature of familiars.  They're not summoned creatures, they are pre-existing creatures who have formed a bond with their wizards.<br>
<br>
3) Familiar is NOT a combatant, nor can it be controlled like a pet.<br>
<br>
4) The familiar talking and interacting with the wizard.  Someone posted this earlier and had me cracking up with the dialogue.<br>
<br>
Some stuff that was touched on, but I'd like to add to:<br>
<br>
1) From what I've read, wizards were able to draw power from their familiars.  In Everquest this could result in lower cast time, increased spell damage, better efficiency, faster mana regen, larger mana pool, lower mob's resistance to spell (this is in relation to adding &quot;power&quot; to the spell.  Draughts could now be resisted like Lures, and Lures could be irresistable), enhance the effects of non-damage spells (roots and snares could hold better and last longer, the skin spells offer better protection etc.), fizzle rates drop, etc.  The benefit(s) of the familiar would increase with level.<br>
<br>
2) If familiar loses too much health, it flees.  In doing so the mental link is broken, draining some of the wizard's mana as well as stunning him or her.  Now, to convince the familiar to return may depend upon the creature.  It may ask for a sacrifice in blood, it may need to be bribed with gems, or it may need to see your repentence through good deeds and charitable acts.  Basically the familiar feels betrayed and will require substantial compensation before trusting you again.<br>
<br>
Other points I'm either split on, or have no ideas how to fix:<br>
<br>
1) The whole zone crossing thing that affects pets.<br>
<br>
2) Whether to pick the animal type of the familiar or have it be random. (I think most would like to have options, but from the books I've read the wizard and familiar didn't choose eachother but rather just became aware of a preexisting connection and therefore of the fact that they &quot;belong&quot; to eachother.)<br>
<br>
